China's Investment Reliance
Beijing—Unexpectedly, China's economy slowed down in the second quarter of this year.
Equally unexpected, most of the data released since July have indicated that China's growth has stabilized.
It's no surprise that the markets have simultaneously exhaled a sigh of relief.
But should investors remain on edge?
The most serious problem currently faced by Chinese authorities is overcapacity.
For example, China's annual crude steel production capacity is 10 billion tons, but the total output in 2012 was only 7.2 billion tons — — the capacity utilization rate was 72%.
More strikingly, the profit margin of the steel industry in 2012 was only 0.04%.
In fact, the profit from producing one ton of steel could only buy one lollipop.
So far this year, the average profit margin of China's top 500 companies is 4.34%, down 33 basis points from 2012.
Some say today's overcapacity stems from excessive investment in the past.
Others believe overcapacity is due to insufficient effective demand.
The government's view seems to be a compromise between the two.
On one hand, the authorities have asked thousands of companies to reduce their capacity.
On the other hand, the government has introduced some "mini-stimulus" measures, such as exempting "micro-enterprises" from business taxes and sales taxes, and requiring banks to increase loans to export-oriented enterprises.
The official stance of the authorities is that China's growth model needs to reduce investment and increase consumption.
But not all Chinese economists agree with this.
They believe that the stock of capital is a key factor for growth, and China's per capita capital stock is still relatively low compared to developed countries, which means there is still a large space for future investment.
Indeed, capital accumulation is a major driver of economic growth, and catching up with the income levels of developed countries requires China to increase its capital stock in the long term.
But what is important is not the scale of the capital stock, or even the level of investment; what is important is the growth rate of investment, which has been much higher than the GDP growth rate for decades.
According to official statistics, China's investment rate has approached 50% of GDP.
Thanks to absorption constraints, capital efficiency steadily declines as the scale of capital increases.
If we take into account the environmental damage caused by the rapidly growing investment, China's capital efficiency would be even lower.
The role of human capital and technological progress in economic growth is no less than that of physical capital and labor.
If the reallocation of resources toward physical capital comes at the expense of human capital accumulation — which is an indispensable condition for sufficient consumption — economic growth is more likely to slow down rather than accelerate.
Therefore, China should reduce the growth rate of investment and increase the growth rate of consumption, stabilizing the investment rate at a more sustainable level.
Of course, it is not entirely wrong to say that China's overcapacity reflects insufficient effective demand.
But where does effective demand come from?
In this regard, China's steel industry again provides a good example.
Although China has no comparative advantage in steel production, it still built about a thousand steel plants, with output accounting for half of the world's total production.
As early as 2004, the Chinese government tried to cool down excessive investment; however, due to the strong demand brought about by infrastructure investment and real estate development, output still grew rapidly, increasing from 3 billion tons that year to 10 billion tons in 2012.
China's investment can generally be divided into three parts: manufacturing, infrastructure, and the real estate industry.
At the peak of the global financial crisis in late 2008 and 2009, infrastructure investment driven by economic stimulus maintained output growth.
In 2010, real estate development investment replaced infrastructure investment as the main driver of growth.
Today, both infrastructure and real estate are important drivers of China's growth.
China indeed needs more infrastructure investment — especially in power and hydropower, transportation and communication.
But the pace of investment must fully take into account financial constraints.
More importantly, China can and should invest more in social infrastructure such as schools, hospitals, and nursing homes.
But real estate investment is another matter.
It is difficult to judge the severity of China's real estate bubble and when it might burst.
But one thing is certain: China has invested far too much in real estate development.
China's per capita income is less than $6,000, yet China's homeownership rate is as high as about 90%, while the United States is less than 70%.
The per capita housing area is 32.9 square meters, while the median housing area for families in Hong Kong is just 48 square meters.
China has 696 five-star hotels, with another 500 under construction.
Out of the ten tallest buildings under construction, five are located in China.
In my view, this can only be described as madness.
China's economy is being held hostage by real estate investment.
On one hand, China should not solve overcapacity by maintaining a high growth rate in real estate investment.
Social housing investment is welcome, but the current real estate investment, accounting for as high as 10–13% of GDP, is already too high.
On the other hand, if real estate investment growth declines, overcapacity cannot be eliminated.
This dilemma highlights the structural adjustment challenges facing China — — and should also keep investors cautious.
In summary, there are two points worth being alert to.
First, unlike other types of investment, real estate investment does not increase productive capital stock.
There is no fundamental difference between houses and high-priced durable consumer goods.
Second, in China's statistical data, the growth rate of total fixed asset investment is significantly higher than the growth rate of total capital formation.
This indicates that the growth rate of fixed investment may overstate the speed of capital stock accumulation.
Therefore, although the Chinese government should resolutely reduce the economy's reliance on investment, the actions must be very cautious.
